Also his more careful discrimination checks the loose credulity of Di0, whose bewildered judgment seems at last to take refuge ina desperate attempt to reconcile conflicting testimony by fusi0n; in the statement that Tiberius ‘had many virtues and many vices, and exercised each as if they had been his only qualities ⁶.'

The appeal from Tacitus appears thus to lie to Tacitus alone ; to his candour and sense of nuth, to hisadmissions ol fact ; against his insinua· tiops and interpretations of motives, against his evident prejudices. That he was no friend to the founders of the principate has been already shown²; and, with all allowance for the sincerity of his diselaimer⁸, special grounds of animosity against Tiberius appear discernible. He had seen in his own day ‘the extremity of slavery, when even the inter· change of speech and hearing was destroyed by espionage ⁹.'
